  "texts": [
    "3 will give an upper bound that matches the lower bound of Lemma 2.5.",
    "Upper Bounds in Prior Work {U(2), CNOT} gate setTo the best of our knowledge, the state-of-the-art quantum state preparation [17,18] methods achieve the following depth, where a is the number of ancillae available:D exact =    Θ( 2 n n), if a = 0 (need n data qubits) Θ( 2 n n+a), if a = O(2 n /n) Θ(n), if a = Ω( 2 n n)Here D exact labels the depth of the exact quantum state preparation circuit using the {U(2), CNOT} gate set, a denotes the number of ancillae, and n denotes the number of qubits of the desired arbitrary quantum state to be prepared.We can compute the spacetime allocation upper bound by simply multiplying the depth with the number of qubits required; we find that the lower bound of Ω(2 n) is saturated for any choice of ancilla qubits a < O(2 n /n), and in particular:SA exact = Θ(2 n), if D exact = Θ( 2 n n) Θ(2 n), if D exact = Θ(n)Interestingly, Sun et al. [17] also proved a depth lower bound of Ω(n) for circuits that use arbitrary single-qubit and two-qubit gates, regardless of the number of ancillary qubits from a graph theory perspective.",
    "3, we show that our SP+CSP state preparation protocol can also achieve Θ(n) depth and Θ(2 n) spacetime allocation.",
    "This provides an alternative construction to that of Ref.",
    "[18], which is also optimal."
